From a8124d8cb9038237ce7937ad695a94c816046839 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Thom de Hoog <thom.dehoog@zmb.uzh.ch>
Date: Wed, 8 Jul 2026 16:08:32 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] Add optional Remote Control tab: TCP + MCP named-call server
 (validated)

mesoSPIM-control has no external control interface -- everything runs in-process
inside the Qt event loop. This adds an optional Remote Control tab that lets
another process drive the microscope over a socket by NAMED CALLS, not code: the
client sends one single-key JSON object {"<method>": {args}}, the server
validates it, looks the method up in a fixed allowlist, and runs the matching
Core call (the same methods the GUI's own buttons call). No client Python is ever
executed.

- mesoSPIM_RemoteControl_ValidateAndRunCommands.py (new): the command vocabulary
  (the COMMANDS allowlist) and _validate, which rejects a call whose args are the
  wrong TYPE, name an option the live cfg does not allow (filter/zoom/laser/
  shutterconfig), or fall out of RANGE -- for EVERY settable parameter, not just the
  stage: axis moves against the loaded config's travel envelope (cfg.stage_parameters,
  optionally tightened per axis by MESOSPIM_RS_LIMITS), intensity/percentages against
  0..100. The error names the limit, so a script/LLM can correct itself, and get_limits
  reports the exact rules (range null = check OFF). run() is the single choke point
  both transports share, so TCP and MCP can never breach a limit -- an out-of-range
  call comes back as an error, never reaching the Core. A PRE-FLIGHT SELF-TEST
  (self_test) runs the whole validated dispatch against a SimCore that carries the
  real cfg but mimics the hardware, proving the loaded limits are enforced before
  the server goes live; it is also an on-demand command on both lanes.
- mesoSPIM_RemoteControl_Servers.py (new): a framed-TCP server hosted by the Core
  and a standalone MCP-over-HTTP server (a separate process) that forwards MCP
  tool calls to the same TCP command path, so both protocols share one validated
  dispatch. The TCP server runs the self-test on start and REFUSES to bind (fail-
  closed) if the loaded limits are not enforced, so the instrument is never exposed
  by a drifted config. Length-framed UTF-8; constant-time token; MCP adds a Bearer
  token and an Origin guard (rejects any non-localhost web origin).
- mesoSPIM_Core: start_remote_control(host, port, token) / stop_remote_control()
  slots (queued, so the server lives on the Core's own thread), plus a
  sig_remote_control_started(ok, message) signal so a bind failure is reported
  rather than shown as a false "running".
- mesoSPIM_MainWindow: a Remote Control tab (TCP / MCP mode, host / port / token +
  generator) that reflects the real start outcome and stops on app close.
- test_remote_control_validation.py: Qt-free tests for the validation gate.

OFF BY DEFAULT and secure-by-default: the server never runs until an operator
starts it from the tab; it binds 127.0.0.1 and pre-fills a fresh token. A named
call controls the instrument (moves the stage, runs acquisitions) but is not
arbitrary code -- the server only ever does a dict lookup + a fixed call, so
nothing outside the allowlist can run. Plain TCP: the token gates casual LAN
access, it is not sniffer-proof (tunnel it for untrusted networks).
